author: robwarriors62
comment: This is actually brilliant songwriting. The modulation at 2:25 isn't just a ham-fisted semitone/half-step lift that most songs do, it's actually set-up beautifully by the intro sequence chords that were established from the start - Am, *F7*, Dm7, E7, Am where the F7 is the V of the new key, Bb minor. Little connections like this go a long way to making your song musically cohesive.

"in a rich mans world" I believe this line does a great job illustrating how the sexist class culture pressures women to work lower paying jobs such as secretaries. author: War commentary
comment: The T-34 is a Soviet medium tank introduced in 1940. Its 76.2 mm (3 in) tank gun was more powerful than its contemporaries while its 60 degree sloped armour provided good protection against anti-tank weapons. The Christie suspension was inherited from the design of American J. Walter Christie's M1928 tank, versions of which were sold turret-less to the Red Army and documented as "farm tractors", after being rejected by the U.S. Army.[citation needed] The T-34 had a profound effect on the conflict on the Eastern Front in the Second World War, and had a lasting impact on tank design. After the Germans encountered the tank in 1941 during Operation Barbarossa, German general Paul Ludwig Ewald von Kleist called it "the finest tank in the world" and Heinz Guderian affirmed the T-34's "vast superiority" over German tanks. Alfred Jodl, chief of operations staff of the German armed forces noted in his war diary "the surprise at this new and thus unknown wunder-armament being unleashed against the German assault divisions," although its armour and armament were surpassed later in the war. The T-34 was the mainstay of Soviet Red Army armoured forces throughout the war. Its general specifications remained nearly unchanged until early 1944, when it received a firepower upgrade with the introduction of the greatly improved T-34-85 variant. Its production method was continuously refined and rationalized to meet the needs of the Eastern Front, making the T-34 quicker and cheaper to produce. The Soviets ultimately built over 80,000 T-34s of all variants, allowing steadily greater numbers to be fielded despite the loss of tens of thousands in combat against the German Wehrmacht. Replacing many light and medium tanks in Red Army service, it was the most-produced tank of the war, as well as the second most-produced tank of all time (after its successor, the T-54/T-55 series). With 44,900 lost during the war, it also suffered the most tank losses ever. Its development led directly to the T-44, then the T-54 and T-55 series of tanks, which in turn evolved into the later T-62, that form the armoured core of many modern armies. T-34 variants were widely exported after World War II, and as recently as 2010 more than 130 were still in service.

author: Chelsea Fooball
comment: I come from Vietnam. ABBA is my favorite band. When I was a child, the Internet was not developed. I don't know who ABBA is. But I heard their music at that time every New Year on TV was "Happy New Year" 's song. This song is very famous and popular in Vietnam. Almost everyone has heard it many times in their life. But people don't know this song from the Swedish group ABBA. When I grew up, the Internet starts to grow , so I'm listening their songs. Yes, their songs are the best. ABBA fills a special place in my heart. It can be said that ABBA is the greatest artist of all time. You guys are so happiness to be born in western countries and listen to ABBA music in the 70s and 80s. If I were to be born again, I wish I had been born in Sweden at that time.

author: chelseacharger
comment: As far as I recall, ABBA made this song as a swipe at their critics who seemed obsessed with the money the group was making at the time. "More profitable than Volvo" and stuff like that. And although their record label got involved in all sorts of business deals to supplement their income, it's understandable. Sweden had an eye watering 85% tax rate for big earners. During the years the group was active, none of the four members moved abroad to a tax haven and they lived remarkably modestly compared to the excesses of many of the rock / pop stars of the 70's.
